WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.105 --> 00:00:03.980
KAI HALEY: All right.

00:00:03.980 --> 00:00:05.100
Welcome.

00:00:05.100 --> 00:00:07.140
Thank you all for joining me.

00:00:07.140 --> 00:00:10.120
I'm very excited to be here
today to talk to you guys

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:14.970
about how design sprints
are flexing for success.

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:17.740
I wanted to start by
introducing myself.

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:19.220
I'm Kai Haley.

00:00:19.220 --> 00:00:22.080
I'm a user experience
designer and I'm also

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:25.420
a lead of our Sprint
Master Academy at Google.

00:00:25.420 --> 00:00:29.300
How many of you are familiar
with design sprints?

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:30.620
Awesome.

00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:34.270
How many have you been
in a design sprint?

00:00:34.270 --> 00:00:35.160
Fantastic.

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:37.130
That's really exciting.

00:00:37.130 --> 00:00:40.110
For those of you who are not
familiar with design sprints,

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:43.320
it's a framework, a
collaboration framework

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:46.770
for answering critical business
questions through design

00:00:46.770 --> 00:00:49.900
prototyping and user research.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:52.570
And the Sprint Master
Academy is a program

00:00:52.570 --> 00:00:55.230
we have at Google
for training people

00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:58.640
to be sprint masters, to
lead and run design sprints.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:00.710
So I run the curriculum,
I create the curriculum

00:01:00.710 --> 00:01:02.730
with a group of
passionate people,

00:01:02.730 --> 00:01:06.420
and I've trained close
to 300 people at Google.

00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:07.880
I'm also a Sprint
Master and I run

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:10.380
a lot of sprints
for various teams

00:01:10.380 --> 00:01:16.130
at Google, as well as outside
with our partners and startups

00:01:16.130 --> 00:01:17.290
and even some nonprofits.

00:01:17.290 --> 00:01:19.010
So I'm really excited
and passionate

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:22.660
about this methodology and happy
to share it with you today.

00:01:22.660 --> 00:01:26.210
I wanted to start
with a personal story.

00:01:26.210 --> 00:01:29.040
When I joined Google
five years ago,

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:31.520
my design and product
development cycle

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:32.990
looked a little bit like this.

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:38.810
Product manager would come to
me with a request or an idea

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:40.250
wanting me to make some mocks.

00:01:40.250 --> 00:01:42.640
And I would ask them
a lot of questions

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:45.010
and try to figure out
what they wanted to do,

00:01:45.010 --> 00:01:48.170
spend some time making the
mocks, maybe a week or two,

00:01:48.170 --> 00:01:50.090
send it back to them.

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:52.630
Invariably there would
have been miscommunications

00:01:52.630 --> 00:01:54.630
and we would need to make
another round of edits

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:56.060
or changes.

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:58.730
We would work on that,
and if I was really lucky,

00:01:58.730 --> 00:02:02.330
we'd be good enough to send
it off to the development team

00:02:02.330 --> 00:02:04.220
to be built.

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:07.110
Usually the engineer
would have a lot of ideas

00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:09.970
and a perspective as well,
and ask a lot of questions,

00:02:09.970 --> 00:02:13.212
and sometimes even
send it back and say,

00:02:13.212 --> 00:02:14.920
there's no way we're
going to build this.

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:16.140
Come on, guys.

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:20.540
So this might take four weeks,
it might take five weeks,

00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:22.570
and never at any
point in this process

00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:25.130
did we take it to
our users and say,

00:02:25.130 --> 00:02:26.305
do you guys even want this?

00:02:26.305 --> 00:02:27.680
Is this going to
meet your needs?

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:30.410
Is it going to solve
some of your pain points?

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:33.950
So you can see how
inefficient this process is.

00:02:33.950 --> 00:02:36.510
It's not a great way
of collaborating,

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:39.490
and frustrating for
everybody involved.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:43.080
I was lucky enough to
participate in the first sprint

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:44.050
week at Google.

00:02:44.050 --> 00:02:47.370
The Ads and Commerce
team brought together

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:49.320
people from different
product areas

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:53.220
to spend a week focused
on innovating new ideas.

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:56.440
And this was really
inspiring and exciting to me.

00:02:56.440 --> 00:02:59.570
I was so enthralled
with this process

00:02:59.570 --> 00:03:01.820
that I volunteered to
become a sprint master

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:03.990
right at that moment
and started running

00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:07.300
design sprints with my team,
with other teams at Google.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.120
And it really changed my
life and changed the way

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:11.720
that I work.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:13.700
So it's really amazing.

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:18.260
And what it does is bring
product managers, UX designers,

00:03:18.260 --> 00:03:22.131
researchers, developers all
into the conversation together.

00:03:22.131 --> 00:03:24.380
These perspectives are all
being added to the strategy

00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:27.340
conversation at the beginning,
and this really increases

00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:32.500
collaboration and improves
actually executable ideas,

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:34.870
because everyone's able to
put their input in together.

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:39.890
So it's really a
cross-functional process.

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:42.990
So today I want
to share with you

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:46.230
how you can use sprints in your
product development lifecycle

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:49.200
from idea all the way
to launch and beyond.

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:51.750
I'm going to talk a little
bit at a high level about what

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:56.580
design sprints are and then
share three examples of how

00:03:56.580 --> 00:04:00.180
teams are using sprints
to create success

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:02.564
for their products.

00:04:02.564 --> 00:04:03.730
So what is a designs sprint?

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:06.195
It sounds like a lot of you
are pretty familiar with this,

00:04:06.195 --> 00:04:08.440
so I'll try to go
through this quickly.

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:10.920
As I mentioned before,
it's a framework

00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:13.400
for answering a critical
business question.

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:16.160
Maybe you want to know how
to increase your customer

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:17.220
acquisition.

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:20.519
Maybe you want to improve
specific small flow

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:23.880
of your product, like improve
your onboarding experience.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:27.060
Maybe you want to create a new
product and brand new vision.

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:28.894
Sprints can be
used for any stage.

00:04:28.894 --> 00:04:30.810
They can be used at the
beginning, the middle,

00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:34.900
and as you evolve over time.

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:38.657
Really, it's a
shortcut to learning.

00:04:38.657 --> 00:04:40.490
Rather than going through
this process where

00:04:40.490 --> 00:04:41.910
you start with an
idea, you spend

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:45.050
a lot of time building it
and getting it exactly right

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:46.820
and then launching
it out into the world

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:50.700
and learning at that point, we
shortcut that and get straight

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:51.380
to the learning.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:54.360
And sprints allow us to do this.

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:56.400
So where does this come from?

00:04:56.400 --> 00:05:00.320
It was created at Google by
a couple of different people,

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:02.950
Jake Knapp, Nadya
Direkova, and some others,

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:06.280
and it's evolved over time
among different groups.

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:09.460
But really it's a set of methods
that we've polled and selected

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:13.390
from the greatest hits of
business strategy, design

00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:16.670
thinking, user research,
and even some psychology.

00:05:16.670 --> 00:05:21.500
And we've ordered them in a
specific way, tested that order

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:23.840
to get it just
right so that we are

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:26.737
using the most effective methods
in the most effective way.

00:05:26.737 --> 00:05:28.320
And we've put them
into this framework

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:31.560
to support divergent
and convergent thinking.

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:33.170
So you'll see
throughout this process

00:05:33.170 --> 00:05:36.660
ways in which we diverge
and then converge again.

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:38.660
And we've tested this
for different goals

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:40.826
and different
deliverables over time.

00:05:40.826 --> 00:05:42.700
But the thing that really
makes it different,

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:45.740
and the thing that I have
found so valuable-- because I

00:05:45.740 --> 00:05:49.650
did a lot of design thinking
prior to discovering sprints--

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:53.430
is that we set a clear goal
and a clear deliverable

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:54.490
at the beginning.

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:55.570
We time box it.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:58.520
We don't spend a lot of time,
maybe at most five days.

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:01.140
And it's very user-centered.

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:03.610
We put the user at the
center of that process,

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:06.430
so we know that we're
building the right thing

00:06:06.430 --> 00:06:09.460
for the right people,
and we do this very fast.

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:12.450
So the first phase,
understand, is

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:14.950
where the team gets together
and creates shared knowledge

00:06:14.950 --> 00:06:16.260
and a shared brain.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:18.690
You map out the problem space.

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:21.930
And we do this by
inviting knowledge experts

00:06:21.930 --> 00:06:23.320
to give lightning talks.

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:25.660
These are 10-minute,
really quick talks

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:28.680
on different aspects
of the problem space.

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:30.470
So you might bring
in a business person

00:06:30.470 --> 00:06:32.570
to talk about the
business opportunity.

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:35.630
You might look at
a competitor audit

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:38.220
of what the space looks like.

00:06:38.220 --> 00:06:40.790
You might look at the
technological opportunity

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:42.510
or constraints.

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:45.780
You'll do an existing
audit, talk to users,

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:46.940
these sort of things.

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:49.900
The sprint master will
capture all of this content

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:53.061
that you're creating on
whiteboards and on the walls

00:06:53.061 --> 00:06:54.310
as you're creating the sprint.

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:56.760
So this is like the
visual brain that you're

00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:59.300
using and pulling from
as you generate ideas

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:00.584
throughout the process.

00:07:00.584 --> 00:07:02.000
And we have some
different methods

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.390
for capturing these ideas.

00:07:04.390 --> 00:07:06.440
One of them is called
the How Might We.

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:09.569
And this is a technique for
transforming pain points

00:07:09.569 --> 00:07:10.360
into opportunities.

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:15.010
We listen to our
users, and you might

00:07:15.010 --> 00:07:17.960
hear them say
something like, oh, I

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:19.710
can't remember my passwords.

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:21.380
I have a really hard time.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:23.400
I go to this website,
I go to that app,

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:25.110
and I just can't keep
track of them all.

00:07:25.110 --> 00:07:26.651
The how might me
that you would write

00:07:26.651 --> 00:07:29.677
from that is, how might we help
making password entry easier?

00:07:29.677 --> 00:07:31.510
And so we're looking
for things that are not

00:07:31.510 --> 00:07:33.114
too broad and not too narrow.

00:07:33.114 --> 00:07:35.530
But this is a way to capture
these opportunities as you're

00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:36.904
listening to your
lightning talks

00:07:36.904 --> 00:07:39.310
or listening to your
user interviews.

00:07:39.310 --> 00:07:41.840
We share these so
each team member,

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:44.610
each sprinter gets to
share out the opportunities

00:07:44.610 --> 00:07:45.780
that they've captured.

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:47.010
And then we categorize them.

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:48.140
We affinity map them.

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:50.220
And this helps us
to provide structure

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:52.400
to how we look at
the problem space,

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:54.159
and then allows us
to prioritize, what

00:07:54.159 --> 00:07:55.950
are the opportunities
that we should really

00:07:55.950 --> 00:07:58.750
focus on to have the
most impact for our user?

00:07:58.750 --> 00:08:01.620
And where are we going to
start sketching our ideas?

00:08:01.620 --> 00:08:03.710
We also have a
user journey method

00:08:03.710 --> 00:08:07.530
that allows us to really get
into the mindset of our user.

00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:11.260
We look at their experience
from the first to all the way

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:14.190
through to the end,
experiencing with our product.

00:08:14.190 --> 00:08:17.660
And this allows us to
surface pain points, which

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:19.660
is where we're pulling
those opportunities from.

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:21.600
What does the experience
look like today?

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:23.627
Where are the challenges
and the problems

00:08:23.627 --> 00:08:24.710
that our users are having?

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:26.820
How can we improve
that and create really

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:29.660
a better user journey for them?

00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:31.760
The understand phase
usually concludes

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:35.150
with a team conversation
about what success looks like.

00:08:35.150 --> 00:08:37.059
What should the success
of this product be,

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:38.900
and how do we
drive towards that?

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:43.360
So we're all on the same page
working towards the same goal.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:45.260
Then we move into
the sketch phase,

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:47.560
which is where-- this is
the diverging phase where

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:50.250
we're going to generate
a broad range of ideas.

00:08:50.250 --> 00:08:52.150
And we might start
off by looking

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:54.670
at a comparable problem.

00:08:54.670 --> 00:08:57.030
Often good ideas
are not new ideas.

00:08:57.030 --> 00:08:58.840
They're just borrowed
from other spaces.

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:01.960
So we might go and pull
in some examples of things

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:03.160
to inspire us.

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:05.450
We might do a
note-taking exercise

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:07.150
where we collect our
thoughts, and this

00:09:07.150 --> 00:09:09.730
is to prepare us for our
really, really fast sketching

00:09:09.730 --> 00:09:11.750
that we do called crazy eights.

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:14.920
We give people eight minutes
to sketch eight ideas.

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:16.390
And what this does
is help people

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:18.219
get beyond their first idea.

00:09:18.219 --> 00:09:20.260
You really want to get to
a broad range of ideas,

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:22.870
and often you kind of get
stuck on that first one.

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:26.100
That time boxing motivates
people to come up

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:29.580
with a lot of ideas, and this is
really the individual ideation

00:09:29.580 --> 00:09:33.970
portion of the sprint and
where the meat of the creation

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:35.190
happens.

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:39.350
We close out the sketching
phase by narrowing down

00:09:39.350 --> 00:09:42.000
to a very well-articulated
solution sketch

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:43.270
that each person will create.

00:09:43.270 --> 00:09:44.820
And this is an
opportunity for people

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:47.930
to sketch out what
they think is the best

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:49.150
solution to this problem.

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:51.760
And then they take this
into the design phase,

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:54.560
where the team
decides, as a group,

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:57.304
what it is that they want to
build for their prototype.

00:09:57.304 --> 00:09:58.970
What do they need to
take to their users

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:02.260
in order to get the learnings
that we're trying to get here?

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:05.200
And we use a number of
different methods for deciding.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:07.990
We have a dot voting method,
where we give people three dots

00:10:07.990 --> 00:10:11.244
and we say, pick
the thing that you

00:10:11.244 --> 00:10:13.660
think we should really build
that's going to have the most

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:15.170
impact for our users.

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:16.900
Sometimes we'll do
a heat map voting

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:19.880
where we let people vote
on specific features,

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:23.199
and this lets you
pull and choose

00:10:23.199 --> 00:10:25.240
from the variety of ideas
that have been created.

00:10:25.240 --> 00:10:27.620
You don't have to just
commit to one idea.

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:30.140
And if you find you're getting
a lot of groupthink or people

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:32.590
are all sort of following
one or two people,

00:10:32.590 --> 00:10:34.540
we have a note and
vote method that's

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:37.850
sort of like a secret voting,
which lets people express

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:40.890
their opinion and their
idea more authentically

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:43.640
so we don't have as much
of this group think.

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:46.230
At the end of this
phase, the team

00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:47.890
has come to a
conclusion about what it

00:10:47.890 --> 00:10:49.410
is that they want to prototype.

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:51.210
And moving into the
prototype phase,

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:54.296
they start off by
creating a storyboard.

00:10:54.296 --> 00:10:55.920
And the storyboard
is where you map out

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:58.510
exactly what you want to
build in your prototype.

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:00.510
And this is done
as a group effort.

00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:02.660
The important thing to
remember with prototyping

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:05.540
is, we're not building a
fully functioning prototype.

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:07.540
We're just creating a
real enough experience

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:10.200
to take it to our users to
get the feedback that we want.

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:12.940
So it's like a facade of
the idea that you have.

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:14.550
So if you're
creating an app, you

00:11:14.550 --> 00:11:17.520
might just do a
set of static mocks

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:18.880
that you can click through.

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:22.280
Or if you're creating a
space or an experience,

00:11:22.280 --> 00:11:24.320
you'd want to try to
prototype that actual space

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:26.430
and give people a
feeling for what it is.

00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:31.350
You need to create the most
useful and real experience

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:33.740
so that you can
get your learnings.

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:35.710
And the important
thing here is we also

00:11:35.710 --> 00:11:37.340
do this really, really fast.

00:11:37.340 --> 00:11:40.010
We generally don't spend more
than a day on a prototype.

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:42.650
So it's amazing what you
can accomplish in a day.

00:11:42.650 --> 00:11:46.310
And sometimes we'll even do
it in two or three hours.

00:11:46.310 --> 00:11:48.060
And then we move into
the validate stage,

00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:51.515
and this is the
really exciting moment

00:11:51.515 --> 00:11:52.890
at the end of the
sprint when you

00:11:52.890 --> 00:11:54.700
get to take your
ideas to your users

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:56.380
and get that feedback
and that learning.

00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:58.580
And we encourage
everybody in the sprint

00:11:58.580 --> 00:12:01.620
to be there to get to
hear from their users

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:04.870
and see what their
experience is.

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:08.340
This is also a time when we
might bring in a stakeholder

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:09.510
to get a stakeholder review.

00:12:09.510 --> 00:12:13.670
If you haven't had your
CEO in this context

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:15.500
of the whole sprint,
this is a great time

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:18.200
to get feedback and
validation from them.

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:21.170
And then you can also do a
technical feasibility review

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:24.680
if you need special
engineering input to make sure

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:27.580
that what you designed
you can actually build.

00:12:27.580 --> 00:12:29.204
This is a really
good time to do that.

00:12:29.204 --> 00:12:30.620
And this is the
end of the sprint.

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:33.050
And at this point, you've
got some really good ideas

00:12:33.050 --> 00:12:34.010
on how to move forward.

00:12:34.010 --> 00:12:36.270
And you may end up deciding
to run another sprint,

00:12:36.270 --> 00:12:38.440
but at this point, you've
got some learnings.

00:12:38.440 --> 00:12:40.830
You know what it is
that you want to build,

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:43.490
and you can take the next step.

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:45.860
Space is really
important for sprints.

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:49.280
Conference rooms are not
great for creativity.

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:52.650
So we have a couple different
types of spaces at Google.

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:54.940
This is our garage, which
is a maker space where

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:56.390
we run a lot of our sprints.

00:12:56.390 --> 00:12:58.330
And it's a really
fantastic place to work.

00:12:58.330 --> 00:13:01.390
Gets people out of their chairs,
standing, working together,

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:03.300
writing on whiteboards,
and not just sitting

00:13:03.300 --> 00:13:05.460
at desks falling asleep.

00:13:07.980 --> 00:13:12.150
So many of you, maybe, have
heard of the Google Ventures

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:14.020
Sprint book that's out there.

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:15.990
They have a five-day model.

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:19.400
And if you're a startup and
this is your only product

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:22.290
that you're working on,
spending five days on it

00:13:22.290 --> 00:13:25.590
makes a ton of sense
and is a great use

00:13:25.590 --> 00:13:29.830
of your time to save yourself
weeks and weeks of development

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:30.520
time.

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:32.050
At Google we have
product teams that

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:33.970
are working on many
different products,

00:13:33.970 --> 00:13:35.800
so it can be hard to
get everybody together

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:36.970
for five days.

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:40.690
So sometimes we'll adjust
the schedule a little bit

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:42.780
to accommodate the
needs of our team.

00:13:42.780 --> 00:13:45.100
We'll do some advance
work, some planning.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:46.780
We'll pull those
lightning talks in.

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:48.940
We'll pull in all the research.

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:50.950
And we'll adjust and
compress the amount of time

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:54.450
we spend on our methods to
meet the needs of the team.

00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:56.190
And sometimes we
might even go down

00:13:56.190 --> 00:13:58.274
to two days or even one day.

00:13:58.274 --> 00:13:59.940
There are some one-day
examples that I'm

00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:01.260
going to share with you today.

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:02.720
And in here, the
important thing is

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:04.650
that we are getting validation.

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:06.870
We may just not be getting
it within that one day.

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:09.510
We'll do it later, or
we'll look at other ways

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:10.760
to get that user validation.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:14.685
But the user validation is
really, really important.

00:14:14.685 --> 00:14:16.060
And the way we're
able to do this

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:18.720
is because we have
our sprint masters.

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:22.700
And as I mentioned before,
we have at least 300 now.

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:24.970
And they're all trained
in these methods,

00:14:24.970 --> 00:14:27.270
and they know how to work
with the product teams.

00:14:27.270 --> 00:14:30.590
They help them define their
goals and their deliverables

00:14:30.590 --> 00:14:32.630
and then adjust the
schedule and the agenda

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:36.500
to be realistic to reach
those goals and deliverables.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:38.190
So every sprint
has a sprint master

00:14:38.190 --> 00:14:40.810
who is the facilitator
who works with the team

00:14:40.810 --> 00:14:42.090
to make this happen.

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:45.560
And also depending on where you
are in your product life cycle,

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:48.206
you might be at the
beginning, where

00:14:48.206 --> 00:14:49.580
you're doing a
project initiation

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:50.890
and you might need more time.

00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:53.809
Or you might have
a new forming team,

00:14:53.809 --> 00:14:55.600
so you might also have
collaboration needs.

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:58.120
If you've been working
together for a long time,

00:14:58.120 --> 00:15:00.420
you might have different
needs for what methods

00:15:00.420 --> 00:15:03.810
you want to utilize.

00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:05.960
So the first example I want
to share with you today

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:10.280
is for a team that used sprints
at every stage in their product

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:13.250
life cycle, from
project initiation

00:15:13.250 --> 00:15:15.180
all the way to launch.

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:17.610
And this is a product
called Google Home Services

00:15:17.610 --> 00:15:19.190
which recently launched.

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:22.590
It connects consumers to
qualified local service

00:15:22.590 --> 00:15:23.090
providers.

00:15:23.090 --> 00:15:26.520
So if you need a dishwasher
repairman to come to your house

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:29.230
and fix your dishwasher,
Google Home Services

00:15:29.230 --> 00:15:32.710
can help connect you to
somebody appropriate and nearby

00:15:32.710 --> 00:15:34.520
in an easy way.

00:15:34.520 --> 00:15:37.880
This idea came out of
the 2014 Sprint Week,

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:42.100
where we brought together
150 people for a week working

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:44.370
on 23 different
product ideas ranging

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:49.020
from moonshots and brand new
products to evolving existing

00:15:49.020 --> 00:15:49.970
products.

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:53.620
And the team was
focused on creating

00:15:53.620 --> 00:15:56.420
a vision for the full
product experience.

00:15:56.420 --> 00:15:59.400
And they really wanted to take
this to stakeholders for buy-in

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:01.680
to get project kickoff.

00:16:01.680 --> 00:16:04.710
So they needed a vision deck
as their deliverables and high

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:08.080
fidelity mocks of the key
moments that articulated

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:10.670
that full narrative.

00:16:10.670 --> 00:16:13.910
They were looking at what the
experience was like today,

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:17.850
what it should be in a year,
two years out, and even four

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:18.380
years out.

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:23.490
So they were really looking
at ideal experience over time.

00:16:23.490 --> 00:16:25.900
They started by understanding
the problem space,

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:28.810
doing lightning talks, inviting
some experts to come and talk

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:32.259
to them about what the
experience was like now, what

00:16:32.259 --> 00:16:34.300
the competitive space was
like, what the business

00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:36.990
opportunity was
like, thinking about

00:16:36.990 --> 00:16:39.770
technological requirements.

00:16:39.770 --> 00:16:45.410
We generated how might we's
and prioritized and categorized

00:16:45.410 --> 00:16:46.330
them.

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:50.797
They sketched ideas for what
the different states would

00:16:50.797 --> 00:16:53.380
be in those key moments and what
the overall experience should

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:54.360
look like.

00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:58.340
And they took these early
stage sketches to their users

00:16:58.340 --> 00:16:59.749
to get early validation.

00:16:59.749 --> 00:17:01.290
Because it was a
brand new idea, they

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:03.248
wanted to be sure they
were on the right track.

00:17:03.248 --> 00:17:06.140
Before they even started making
their full-fledged mocks.

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:08.381
They said, does
this fit your needs?

00:17:08.381 --> 00:17:09.839
Is this going to
fit into your flow

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:11.589
of trying to find a plumber?

00:17:11.589 --> 00:17:14.740
And then they responded
to that feedback,

00:17:14.740 --> 00:17:17.690
started working on their
mocks and their prototypes,

00:17:17.690 --> 00:17:20.310
and looking at how can
we help them diagnose

00:17:20.310 --> 00:17:22.740
the problem-- this was
a big pain point that

00:17:22.740 --> 00:17:25.670
came out-- and ended
up with a vision deck

00:17:25.670 --> 00:17:27.420
that they took back
to their stakeholders.

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:29.630
And this project was approved.

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:30.880
The vision deck did its job.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:33.004
Everyone said, wow, this
is a really great concept.

00:17:33.004 --> 00:17:35.685
We absolutely need
to invest in this.

00:17:35.685 --> 00:17:37.830
The schedule for
this sprint, so you

00:17:37.830 --> 00:17:40.210
can take a look at how
this framework has flexed

00:17:40.210 --> 00:17:42.930
a little bit, was three days.

00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:45.800
And they spent the first day
understanding and sketching.

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:48.290
Early validation on day two.

00:17:48.290 --> 00:17:51.070
More sketching, and then
deciding and prototyping

00:17:51.070 --> 00:17:53.540
on the last day.

00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:56.630
After this they
ran another sprint

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:59.670
to look at the
experience from searching

00:17:59.670 --> 00:18:01.700
for a provider to booking
a provider, so just

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:04.800
a small slice of the
product experience.

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:07.467
They really wanted to diverge
and get a broad range of ideas,

00:18:07.467 --> 00:18:09.550
and they wanted to make
sure they were considering

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:14.870
all the different aspects of
this particular set of flows.

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:17.540
And they wanted very
low-fidelity deliverables

00:18:17.540 --> 00:18:20.880
for this, user flows
and sketch mocks.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:23.740
So they identified what were
the steps, what was the piece

00:18:23.740 --> 00:18:26.740
that they wanted to solve for.

00:18:26.740 --> 00:18:29.230
They reviewed existing
research that they'd

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:32.432
done before, a lot of
reminding themselves of,

00:18:32.432 --> 00:18:34.140
these were the pain
points and the things

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:38.670
that we heard, reviewing
competitor experiences, what

00:18:38.670 --> 00:18:41.670
was good about that, what
was not so good about that.

00:18:41.670 --> 00:18:44.369
They generated how might
we's and prioritized those.

00:18:44.369 --> 00:18:45.660
Where should we focus for this?

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:48.240
What are the best ideas
that we have here?

00:18:48.240 --> 00:18:49.580
Sketches.

00:18:49.580 --> 00:18:52.010
And then sketches were really
where they ended the sprint.

00:18:52.010 --> 00:18:55.264
And the UX team took
this back to their desks

00:18:55.264 --> 00:18:57.180
and started actually
building mocks from this.

00:18:57.180 --> 00:18:59.990
So this was kind of a
little turbo boost, more

00:18:59.990 --> 00:19:03.290
of a brainstorming workshop.

00:19:03.290 --> 00:19:05.400
The schedule for
this was a one-day

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:08.000
because they were looking
for pretty low fidelity.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.250
They spent the first portion
of the day understanding,

00:19:10.250 --> 00:19:12.590
and then sketching
and prototyping

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:14.980
in the second half of the day.

00:19:14.980 --> 00:19:17.240
The third sprint
that they ran was

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:20.530
to design the end-to-end
assistive experience,

00:19:20.530 --> 00:19:22.730
so helping people to
diagnose their problem,

00:19:22.730 --> 00:19:26.700
helping them to connect
with a good provider,

00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:29.955
and for both sets of audiences,
consumers and providers.

00:19:29.955 --> 00:19:31.910
So they had two users.

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:35.390
And they wanted a
high-level user journey map

00:19:35.390 --> 00:19:38.730
that would let them create
a prioritized project plan,

00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:41.550
figuring out what exactly do
we have to build for launch,

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:44.430
and what can we save for later?

00:19:44.430 --> 00:19:47.240
They all got together, reviewed
their use cases, thought

00:19:47.240 --> 00:19:50.200
about the goals for the sprint,
what do we need to cover here?

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:52.470
They spent time
thinking about what

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:54.710
are the needs for
each user, generating

00:19:54.710 --> 00:19:58.460
how might we's for the
providers versus the consumers.

00:19:58.460 --> 00:20:00.170
They even did some
more user interviews

00:20:00.170 --> 00:20:02.320
because they wanted to
fill in the gaps on things

00:20:02.320 --> 00:20:04.220
that they had missed before.

00:20:04.220 --> 00:20:07.510
And then they created end-to-end
user-- very, very detailed user

00:20:07.510 --> 00:20:08.010
journeys.

00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:12.180
And they identified specific
steps in the process,

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:13.960
and this helped
them to prioritize.

00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:14.960
Well, maybe we
don't have to worry

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:16.960
so much about the grow
at the end or the promote

00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:17.870
at the beginning.

00:20:17.870 --> 00:20:20.080
To get to launch, we need
to focus on this here

00:20:20.080 --> 00:20:20.800
in the middle.

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:23.670
And that was something that
the team really needed in order

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:25.650
to move forward.

00:20:25.650 --> 00:20:28.480
So they did this in
a day and a half.

00:20:28.480 --> 00:20:31.840
They spent half of the first day
understanding and figuring out

00:20:31.840 --> 00:20:34.510
what they wanted to create,
sketching, deciding,

00:20:34.510 --> 00:20:36.060
and then prototyping
and validating

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:37.559
with the rest of
the team afterwards

00:20:37.559 --> 00:20:40.730
and creating that project map.

00:20:40.730 --> 00:20:43.000
The launch product is
on the search page.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.330
You can go search for
a plumber near you now,

00:20:45.330 --> 00:20:49.360
and you'll get an assistive
UI that will take you

00:20:49.360 --> 00:20:51.550
into an immersive experience
that will help you

00:20:51.550 --> 00:20:53.640
find a plumber for your needs.

00:20:53.640 --> 00:20:55.730
And then you can also
do this on desktop.

00:20:55.730 --> 00:20:57.770
And it really helps
people to connect

00:20:57.770 --> 00:20:59.022
with multiple providers.

00:20:59.022 --> 00:21:00.480
And that was one
of the pain points

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:02.310
that came out of all
of their interviews,

00:21:02.310 --> 00:21:06.040
was managing all of
these different plumbers

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:08.010
is actually really
difficult. So they

00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:12.610
solved for some of those key
problems with this product.

00:21:12.610 --> 00:21:16.000
And they utilized these
sprints at the beginning

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.140
for the kickoff, in the
middle as a turbo boost,

00:21:19.140 --> 00:21:21.920
and then towards the end
to prioritize what they

00:21:21.920 --> 00:21:24.340
needed to build for launch.

00:21:24.340 --> 00:21:26.250
And the outcomes were,
as I mentioned before,

00:21:26.250 --> 00:21:29.570
generating approval to
initiate the project, really

00:21:29.570 --> 00:21:31.240
creating a shared
vision for the team

00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:34.060
to help them know
what they were working

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:37.700
towards over the long term,
giving a little turbo boost

00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:40.170
in the middle to their
design, and then innovating

00:21:40.170 --> 00:21:43.400
ideas towards the end for the
full end-to-end experience.

00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:47.900
The second example I
want to share with you

00:21:47.900 --> 00:21:52.280
is for a team that used a sprint
to actually start a completely

00:21:52.280 --> 00:21:53.740
brand new business.

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:55.530
It was a Project Kickoff.

00:21:55.530 --> 00:21:58.100
And the business is
called HarvestPort.

00:21:58.100 --> 00:22:02.670
It is a marketplace for
sharing agricultural assets

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:06.350
like vegetable bins and farming
equipment and stuff like that,

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:08.710
allowing people to monetize
when they're not using it

00:22:08.710 --> 00:22:10.810
in the offseason.

00:22:10.810 --> 00:22:13.120
And they wanted to define
that product offering

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:15.584
for the new asset
sharing marketplace

00:22:15.584 --> 00:22:17.250
and create a shared
vision for the team.

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:20.040
So they had an idea, but they
really wanted to figure out,

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:22.960
what is this idea and what
does this space look like?

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:25.710
They wanted user flows
and high fidelity mocks

00:22:25.710 --> 00:22:28.590
that they could then take
and build from later.

00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:33.410
So they were looking for
a mid-level of fidelity.

00:22:33.410 --> 00:22:38.690
We all came together and
invited lightning talk speakers,

00:22:38.690 --> 00:22:40.799
experts from the
agricultural industry,

00:22:40.799 --> 00:22:43.340
to come talk to us about what
the business opportunity really

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:45.830
was, what the
existing systems were,

00:22:45.830 --> 00:22:47.769
what the competitive
space looked like.

00:22:47.769 --> 00:22:50.060
And one of the really fantastic
things about this brand

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:52.550
is that we actually had
farmers-- there are two of them

00:22:52.550 --> 00:22:56.470
in this picture here-- with
us for the entire sprint,

00:22:56.470 --> 00:22:59.110
creating how might we's
and sketching with us.

00:22:59.110 --> 00:23:01.280
And this gave us this
constant validation

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:03.940
as we were working together.

00:23:03.940 --> 00:23:07.310
We also interviewed some
potential customers.

00:23:07.310 --> 00:23:08.982
So we did the user
interviews as well

00:23:08.982 --> 00:23:11.190
to get a sense of, what was
the environment that they

00:23:11.190 --> 00:23:11.970
were working in?

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:14.280
What are their Wi-Fi
connections like?

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:16.540
What are their
technological capabilities?

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:19.240
And this really helped
us to understand

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:22.260
the broad base of users.

00:23:22.260 --> 00:23:27.770
We generated how might we's and
prioritized those, and created

00:23:27.770 --> 00:23:30.910
