00:28:03.190 --> 00:28:06.760
So they did one in the fall.

00:28:06.760 --> 00:28:08.670
They had another
one a month ago,

00:28:08.670 --> 00:28:11.040
and they found that
they pull it in whenever

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:14.810
they need some focused
time to really inject speed

00:28:14.810 --> 00:28:17.240
into their process.

00:28:17.240 --> 00:28:19.890
And the UX designer
and developer

00:28:19.890 --> 00:28:21.550
feel a little bit
more like this now.

00:28:21.550 --> 00:28:23.890
They have a better understanding
of each other's working

00:28:23.890 --> 00:28:25.670
methodology, their roles.

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:27.810
And when the developer
is coding and he's

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:31.540
coming across UI challenges
that haven't been resolved,

00:28:31.540 --> 00:28:33.940
he'll now walk over to
the UX designer's desk

00:28:33.940 --> 00:28:36.560
and say, hey, let's solve
this together instead

00:28:36.560 --> 00:28:38.640
of sort of working in silos.

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:42.020
So it's been really fantastic
for their collaboration

00:28:42.020 --> 00:28:44.000
and for their innovation.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:45.780
So the outcomes are a
deeper understanding

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:47.400
of each other's work.

00:28:47.400 --> 00:28:50.220
The designers become a lot
less precious about design,

00:28:50.220 --> 00:28:53.340
not fixating too much on
getting it exactly right,

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:56.190
but trying to get through
an iteration process faster.

00:28:56.190 --> 00:28:58.730
And it's changed the way
they think about prototyping.

00:28:58.730 --> 00:29:01.470
They said prior to this
process, they kind of

00:29:01.470 --> 00:29:03.767
thought about prototyping
as a throwaway activity.

00:29:03.767 --> 00:29:05.850
You're building something,
but you're not actually

00:29:05.850 --> 00:29:08.610
going to use that in
your live product.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:12.250
And so they're trying to shorten
that gap between prototyping

00:29:12.250 --> 00:29:13.320
and building.

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:17.330
And this allowed them to
decrease the time from idea

00:29:17.330 --> 00:29:19.740
to mock to prototype,
and to increase

00:29:19.740 --> 00:29:22.130
the number of executable
ideas, because they're really

00:29:22.130 --> 00:29:23.950
focused in on, is this viable?

00:29:23.950 --> 00:29:25.930
Is this a good idea?

00:29:25.930 --> 00:29:29.070
And created a strong sense
of ownership with the team.

00:29:29.070 --> 00:29:31.080
Everyone really
had an investment

00:29:31.080 --> 00:29:34.780
in the ideas that were created.

00:29:34.780 --> 00:29:36.750
So you can see how
we're shortcutting

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:41.880
getting from idea to learn fast,
and doing this over and over

00:29:41.880 --> 00:29:45.190
and over again
throughout our process

00:29:45.190 --> 00:29:49.390
to really get to an
effective innovation method.

00:29:49.390 --> 00:29:53.970
And we don't approach sprints
in a cookie cutter way.

00:29:53.970 --> 00:29:57.880
No two sprints are the same no
two sprinting team is the same.

00:29:57.880 --> 00:29:59.810
Every product has
different needs.

00:29:59.810 --> 00:30:02.440
And it's a flexible
framework that we use.

00:30:02.440 --> 00:30:05.370
Based on the goals and the
deliverables of the team,

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:08.710
we can adjust in order
to meet those goals.

00:30:08.710 --> 00:30:12.070
So it's a really,
really fantastic method.

00:30:12.070 --> 00:30:15.220
And if you're going to start
thinking about running sprints

00:30:15.220 --> 00:30:18.164
with your teams, it's
important to understand

00:30:18.164 --> 00:30:19.080
what they're good for.

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:21.310
They're really great
for user validation,

00:30:21.310 --> 00:30:25.370
really fantastic for
speed and collaboration.

00:30:25.370 --> 00:30:27.370
So thinking about how
you want to structure

00:30:27.370 --> 00:30:29.150
your sprint for those needs.

