My question is, do you change
[INAUDIBLE] of each step

00:36:07.880 --> 00:36:11.520
while doing the design sprint?

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:14.925
So I think that
sometimes understanding

00:36:14.925 --> 00:36:15.800
may take longer time.

00:36:19.710 --> 00:36:23.940
So that do you have any
tips to arrange [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:28.270
KAI HALEY: Well, it
really depends on what

00:36:28.270 --> 00:36:29.950
your goals and deliverable are.

00:36:29.950 --> 00:36:32.520
And sometimes you'll spend a
lot more time understanding

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:35.220
if your goal is very
broad and if you

00:36:35.220 --> 00:36:37.012
need to spend that
time sort of narrowing

00:36:37.012 --> 00:36:38.970
in on what's going to be
the target that you're

00:36:38.970 --> 00:36:40.100
going to focus on.

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:42.720
So sometimes you might
take a whole day,

00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:44.690
you know, an entire
day for understand.

00:36:44.690 --> 00:36:46.541
And sometimes we might
just take an hour.

00:36:46.541 --> 00:36:48.790
If you have a really good
understanding of the problem

00:36:48.790 --> 00:36:52.319
space and you're just bringing
and surfacing the content,

00:36:52.319 --> 00:36:54.360
and you're not spending
a lot of time discussing.

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:57.870
But in terms of tips
for figuring that out,

00:36:57.870 --> 00:37:02.100
you have to get a read on
the challenge and the team.

00:37:02.100 --> 00:37:04.731
And sometimes people want to
have a lot of conversation.

00:37:04.731 --> 00:37:06.730
And that will lead to a
longer understand phase.

00:37:06.730 --> 00:37:08.440
So I've certainly
been in situations

00:37:08.440 --> 00:37:11.051
where the team needed to have
the conversation because one

00:37:11.051 --> 00:37:12.800
person had one
perspective, another person

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:13.810
had another perspective.

00:37:13.810 --> 00:37:15.750
And in that understand
phase, you're

00:37:15.750 --> 00:37:17.540
sharing those
perspectives and coming

00:37:17.540 --> 00:37:20.684
to a common understanding,
and then making a decision,

00:37:20.684 --> 00:37:23.100
is the product going to be
this or is it going to be that?

00:37:23.100 --> 00:37:25.750
So sometimes that can
take a while, it's true.

00:37:25.750 --> 00:37:28.650
But the thing with the
sprint is, you actually

00:37:28.650 --> 00:37:31.170
have a timer up here, and it's
like, you've got 10 minutes

00:37:31.170 --> 00:37:33.060
to come to a conclusion.

00:37:33.060 --> 00:37:35.750
And you'd be surprised
at what people will

00:37:35.750 --> 00:37:38.260
do when that timer goes off.

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:41.130
They're like, OK, we'll do it.

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:41.910
Yeah.

00:37:41.910 --> 00:37:42.422
Go ahead.

00:37:42.422 --> 00:37:44.755
AUDIENCE: When I've participated
in sprints in the past,

00:37:44.755 --> 00:37:46.780
and the ones you
mentioned today,

00:37:46.780 --> 00:37:49.115
it's been mostly around
launching new features,

00:37:49.115 --> 00:37:50.350
new products.

00:37:50.350 --> 00:37:51.770
I'm curious, from
your experience,

00:37:51.770 --> 00:37:53.490
if you've seen this work
well with other things,

00:37:53.490 --> 00:37:55.930
say, design-driven initiatives,
if you're dealing with,

00:37:55.930 --> 00:37:58.730
say, a lot of product
or design debt

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:02.110
that's like cross-platform
inconsistencies, product

00:38:02.110 --> 00:38:06.800
hierarchy, is this mechanism
effective for helping

00:38:06.800 --> 00:38:09.040
solve those challenges as well?

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:11.830
And a lot of those may
not involve users as much.

00:38:11.830 --> 00:38:13.440
It should always involve users.

00:38:13.440 --> 00:38:16.254
But it's a little bit different,
I would say, kind of process.

00:38:16.254 --> 00:38:16.920
KAI HALEY: Yeah.

00:38:16.920 --> 00:38:19.127
Your users may be more
complex at that point

00:38:19.127 --> 00:38:20.710
because you've got
multiple people who

00:38:20.710 --> 00:38:22.810
are engaging with something.

00:38:22.810 --> 00:38:24.530
It is effective for that.

00:38:24.530 --> 00:38:25.870
It can be more complex.

00:38:25.870 --> 00:38:29.680
And you have to think about
using your time efficiently

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:34.510
and trying to organize the
problem a little bit more.

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:38.320
And I've only done a couple
that are more larger processes

00:38:38.320 --> 00:38:40.110
or cross-platform.

00:38:40.110 --> 00:38:43.380
And what I often do
is I'll divide it.

00:38:43.380 --> 00:38:45.700
So I won't try to tackle
everything in one sprint.

00:38:45.700 --> 00:38:47.380
I'll say, let's
look at this piece,

00:38:47.380 --> 00:38:51.320
and then you solve that and
then take it to the next one.

00:38:51.320 --> 00:38:54.080
So if you can-- even like
that user journey map,

00:38:54.080 --> 00:38:56.400
or you can sort of divide
it up into sections.

00:38:56.400 --> 00:39:00.070
And then each section will
maybe inform the next one.

00:39:00.070 --> 00:39:04.256
But oftentimes you can't bite
off everything all at once.

00:39:04.256 --> 00:39:05.880
But I certainly
encourage you to try it

00:39:05.880 --> 00:39:09.140
with something like that,
because it's a really great

00:39:09.140 --> 00:39:10.470
collaboration method.

00:39:10.470 --> 00:39:12.930
And the other thing
I encourage people

00:39:12.930 --> 00:39:14.760
is to try other methods, too.

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:18.790
I mean, we've selected
30 from over 300

00:39:18.790 --> 00:39:20.279
out there in the world.

00:39:20.279 --> 00:39:21.820
But the framework
is flexible and you

00:39:21.820 --> 00:39:25.370
can pull in other methods as
needed based on your needs.

00:39:28.839 --> 00:39:29.380
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:29.380 --> 00:39:30.880
Can you go into a
little more detail

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:34.200
around what the sprint mater's
role is during the sprint,

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:36.283
and also, who can play that?

00:39:36.283 --> 00:39:38.600
Is it anyone?

00:39:38.600 --> 00:39:39.654
KAI HALEY: Yeah.

00:39:39.654 --> 00:39:41.070
It's really great
to have somebody

00:39:41.070 --> 00:39:43.210
who's good at
facilitation, who is

00:39:43.210 --> 00:39:49.880
able to read the room well
and get a sense of how people

00:39:49.880 --> 00:39:52.830
are feeling and how they're
responding to each other.

00:39:52.830 --> 00:39:56.380
So we often have UX
people because it's

00:39:56.380 --> 00:39:58.090
a very user-centered process.

00:39:58.090 --> 00:39:59.850
But really lots
of different roles

00:39:59.850 --> 00:40:03.210
can take on the role of
facilitator, provided

00:40:03.210 --> 00:40:08.550
that you enjoy that kind of
work where you're oftentimes

00:40:08.550 --> 00:40:13.070
corralling people and asking
people to make decisions.

00:40:13.070 --> 00:40:17.090
And so you have to be
comfortable with sort

00:40:17.090 --> 00:40:19.190
of holding to your
rules and saying,

00:40:19.190 --> 00:40:20.790
OK, well, this is
the time frame,

00:40:20.790 --> 00:40:22.730
and we gotta keep moving.

00:40:22.730 --> 00:40:25.840
So people who are more
used to being taskmasters

00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:28.400
sometimes are helpful,
but that can do it gently,

00:40:28.400 --> 00:40:31.490
because-- I mean, I always
start a sprint and say,

00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:33.070
I'm going to move you along.

00:40:33.070 --> 00:40:34.300
I'm going to cut you off.

00:40:34.300 --> 00:40:34.950
It's a sprint.

00:40:34.950 --> 00:40:36.800
We're going to move fast.

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:41.330
So people who are good at that.

00:40:41.330 --> 00:40:46.080
And the important thing is being
able to pivot at any moment

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:49.020
during the sprint, because
you're learning new things

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:50.520
throughout the whole process.

00:40:50.520 --> 00:40:53.420
And at any point in time you
might just adjust everything.

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:55.560
And so you'll change
your schedule,

00:40:55.560 --> 00:40:58.150
and you may end up
changing your deliverables.

00:40:58.150 --> 00:41:00.600
So you have to be flexible
and able to think on your feet

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:04.540
really well and have a
good sense of product

00:41:04.540 --> 00:41:06.410
problem solving,
like really helping

00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:07.978
the group problem solve.

00:41:07.978 --> 00:41:09.770
AUDIENCE: So that
person isn't sketching,

00:41:09.770 --> 00:41:11.220
isn't doing the process.

00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:13.760
They're the kind of bystander
that moves it along.

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:15.350
KAI HALEY: They are
the facilitator.

00:41:15.350 --> 00:41:21.080
And sometimes they might
interject some ideas.

00:41:21.080 --> 00:41:24.080
And I've certainly run sprints
for my team and my product

00:41:24.080 --> 00:41:26.740
area, and I'm a designer
so I'm invested in it.

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:28.740
It's a little bit harder,
because you really

00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:30.280
want to sketch and
generate ideas,

00:41:30.280 --> 00:41:33.370
but you're exhausted from
getting everybody excited

00:41:33.370 --> 00:41:35.330
and keeping everybody
focused and engaged

00:41:35.330 --> 00:41:37.620
and talking them
through every exercise.

00:41:37.620 --> 00:41:40.190
So generally we
recommend that people

00:41:40.190 --> 00:41:43.110
don't try to be a sprinter
and a sprint master.

00:41:43.110 --> 00:41:45.460
We say you'll be much more
effective if you focus

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:47.850
on just being a sprint
master, and look

00:41:47.850 --> 00:41:50.836
at the process as opposed to
the content of the sprint.

00:41:55.390 --> 00:41:57.630
AUDIENCE: So I have a
question around when

00:41:57.630 --> 00:42:01.033
you go into a sprint, it could
be that you're spending a day

00:42:01.033 --> 00:42:03.325
or two working
together, collaborating,

00:42:03.325 --> 00:42:05.830
and you have to kind of
block out your schedule.

00:42:05.830 --> 00:42:08.260
And how do you cancel
out all the other noise

00:42:08.260 --> 00:42:11.040
that's coming in from other
projects and other PMs?

00:42:11.040 --> 00:42:13.797
And how can you just
focus on one thing

00:42:13.797 --> 00:42:15.630
and not worry about the
million other things

00:42:15.630 --> 00:42:16.490
that you have to do?

00:42:16.490 --> 00:42:17.980
KAI HALEY: It's
really challenging.

00:42:17.980 --> 00:42:19.610
It's very challenging for teams.

00:42:19.610 --> 00:42:21.490
Sometimes we'll go offsite.

00:42:21.490 --> 00:42:24.560
So we'll take the whole
team to another location,

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:27.720
and then people can't duck out
for meetings and take calls.

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:29.210
And you change
their environment,

00:42:29.210 --> 00:42:30.690
and then everyone can focus.

00:42:30.690 --> 00:42:33.107
So that's one thing you can do.

00:42:33.107 --> 00:42:35.440
We set the ground rules for
the sprint at the beginning.

00:42:35.440 --> 00:42:38.940
We say, we're asking you to
be here for this time period.

00:42:38.940 --> 00:42:41.260
If you need to jump out
for one call, that's fine.

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:42.700
But if you're in
a sprint, you're

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:44.460
in a sprint from the
beginning to the end,

00:42:44.460 --> 00:42:46.650
because it's very disruptive
to jump in and out.

00:42:46.650 --> 00:42:49.320
And you're really creating
this collaborative space

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:50.680
and this team.

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:53.210
So when people
leave, it disrupts

00:42:53.210 --> 00:42:55.480
that team building
that's happening

00:42:55.480 --> 00:42:59.460
and the effectiveness
of working together.

00:42:59.460 --> 00:43:03.110
So it's a challenge, though.

00:43:03.110 --> 00:43:04.790
At Google it's become a culture.

00:43:04.790 --> 00:43:07.690
So every team here is sprinting.

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:10.940
And so people are more used,
to seeing the auto response,

00:43:10.940 --> 00:43:12.280
I'm in a sprint for three days.

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:14.539
Sorry I'll get back to
you at the end of the day.

00:43:14.539 --> 00:43:16.580
So there's a little bit
more of that expectation.

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:19.970
And I think as you're
able to make that culture

00:43:19.970 --> 00:43:24.390
shift within a company,
that will help some, to say,

00:43:24.390 --> 00:43:26.780
OK, this is actually something
that we're all doing.

00:43:26.780 --> 00:43:31.020
And so we'll respect
about space and that time.

00:43:31.020 --> 00:43:32.320
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:33.740
KAI HALEY: Absolutely.

00:43:33.740 --> 00:43:35.337
OK.

00:43:35.337 --> 00:43:36.170
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:37.380
I guess this works
perfectly, because I

00:43:37.380 --> 00:43:39.710
was going to ask you about
the timeline that you set up.

00:43:39.710 --> 00:43:41.376
Have you found that
it's better to do it

00:43:41.376 --> 00:43:44.000
in a block of a day as
opposed to two hours one day,

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:45.210
three hours a day?

00:43:45.210 --> 00:43:46.420
KAI HALEY: Absolutely.

00:43:46.420 --> 00:43:49.310
Well, the framework and the
process, like I was saying,

00:43:49.310 --> 00:43:52.540
the methods are ordered
to build into each other.

00:43:52.540 --> 00:43:55.030
So as you create this
shared knowledge,

00:43:55.030 --> 00:43:56.630
as you create all
these opportunities,

00:43:56.630 --> 00:43:58.990
it starts to generate
ideas in your head.

00:43:58.990 --> 00:44:00.610
And then if you
jump into sketching,

00:44:00.610 --> 00:44:02.620
you've got those
ideas and it's really

00:44:02.620 --> 00:44:07.670
this-- you have this
brainstorm and creative moment.

00:44:07.670 --> 00:44:11.790
If you wait another week,
all of that is gone.

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:15.110
So the stages build
into each other,

00:44:15.110 --> 00:44:17.690
and so that's the other reason
why we do it all in a row.

00:44:17.690 --> 00:44:21.640
And we give people breaks,
and sometimes we do 10 to 5

00:44:21.640 --> 00:44:24.570
instead of 9 to 5 and try
not to wear people out.

00:44:24.570 --> 00:44:29.850
But I always encourage
people to do it in succession

00:44:29.850 --> 00:44:32.380
and not break up and kill
that creative moment,

00:44:32.380 --> 00:44:35.000
because this is really about
innovation and ideation.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:38.550
And we're setting it up so
that you are in the best place

00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:40.320
to generate the best ideas.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:41.290
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:41.290 --> 00:44:43.670
KAI HALEY: Absolutely.

